      <h1>My Story</h1>
      <h2>The self indulgent ramblings of an armchair fan in Dunblane.</h2>
      <h2>From the pain of '86 to the pride of '26.</h2>
      <h2>This is my story...</h2>

      <div class="stats">
        <a class="stat position-stat" href="#early-years">
          The<strong>Early Years</strong>
        </a>
        <a class="stat position-stat" href="#the-season">
          The<strong>Season</strong>
        </a>
        <a class="stat position-stat" href="#the-future">
          The<strong>Future</strong>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <main class="shell">
    <section id="early-years" class="match-section">
      <article class="panel story-panel" style="line-height:1.7">
        <button class="story-disclaimer" type="button" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="story-disclaimer-heading">
            <span class="story-panel-title">The Early Years</span>
            <small>
              <a href="#top" class="back-to-top">Back to top ↑</a>
            </small>
          </span>

          <span class="story-warning">
            This section is hidden by default due to danger of extreme boredom.<br
            />
            Click this banner to continue at your own risk. You have been warned...
          </span>
        </button>

        <div class="story-content">
          <p>
            Honestly, skip this bit if you're only interested in the fitba. This
            is my own story about me and my journey during the 2025/26 season -
            I need to heal, so I'm gonna be indulgent and start from the
            beginning.
          </p>

          <p>
            One of my first memories was when a boy called Gav joined my class
            in Primary Two and asked me what football team I supported. My dad
            was (and still is) a rugby man, so I don't think I'd ever really
            thought about it. I said I was a Hibs fan - he said Hibs were crap
            and I should be a Hearts fan. It was Corstorphine —
            <i
              >well, Carrick Knowe actually, I'm just trying to posh myself up
              here</i
            > — so it made sense. It was closer to Tynecastle. From then on, I was
            a Jambo.
          </p>

          <p>
            Having an egg-chaser as a dad, I didn't get to many games. My family
            were big into the church and Scouting, so every weekend was either a
            jumble sale, a church fair or putting camping equipment in the attic
            of the Scout hall. And given it was Thatcher's Scotland and my folks
            didn't have two pennies to rub together, the chances of me visiting
            Tynecastle were fairly limited. However, a man called Derek, who
            later became my scout leader, took me to a few games. I remember a
            Dumbarton game, a Motherwell game, and I was even there when PSG
            came to Tynecastle and we came away with a 2–2 draw.
          </p>

          <p>
            Then came '86. Those who remember it will sympathise with a
            ten-year-old boy sitting watching Ceefax and listening to Radio
            Scotland, seeing the images on the news of grown men greetin' their
            eyes out and throwing things at that moustachioed, curly-haired
            twat, albert kidd (sorry for even mentioning his name). It was a
            horrible time, and it has lived with me till this day - my poor
            family, friends, and colleagues will attest how much it affected me,
            even 40 years later
          </p>

          <p>
            Primary school — and Gav — came and went. High school beckoned. A
            new best pal, Derek (not my scout leader), and even more Jambos at
            Forrester High School. Still no money, and as it was the 80s, live
            football was seriously limited. For years, everything was Hearts —
            Hearts bedsheets, Hearts wallpaper, Hearts annuals. I was Hearts
            daft. I lived round the corner from Neil Berry and saw him
            regularly. Posters of Robbo and Gary Mackay on every wall. We've all
            been there, and I wouldn't change it for anything.
          </p>

          <p>
            After high school, I left Edinburgh for Aberdeen and university. I
            left Derek in Edinburgh, working in the bank, with his season ticket
            at Tynecastle. I got right into booze and drugs (and subsequently
            got kicked out of uni, and then college), and the hero worshipping
            of the boys in maroon started to fade for a while. Living with
            Rangers fans during the nine-in-a-row era was tough - they were
            never, and still aren't, the most gracious of winners - but I still
            listened on the radio and watched on the telly, but let's be honest
            — my mind was elsewhere.
          </p>

          <p>
            I left Aberdeen seven years later with my Aberdeen supporting
            girlfriend (later becoming wife) and ended up back in Edinburgh.
            When Derek couldn't go to the fitba, I'd get his ticket, so I saw a
            good few games. He sat with his pal Rab where the "ultras" bang
            their drums now. Had a bit more cash, so got to a few more games -
            but working in retail meant Saturdays were for work, not fitba. But
            Saw Barcelona at Tynecastle. Saw Bayern at Pittodrie on Valentine's
            Day. We all remember the Romanov era - it was a rollercoaster (think
            Codona's rather than Alton Towers), and thank Christ it's over. But
            thanks to some amazing people, we came out the other side and we all
            owe them a great deal that our club is in the position it is now.
            Ann Budge came into my kilt shop and I ended up getting involved in
            the new Hearts tartan. Ended up doing a photoshoot with John Souttar
            and Don Cowie and met loads of Jambo legends, including Craig Levein
            and Gary Locke. It was a great time.
          </p>

          <p>
            I ended up in Linlithgow watching games in the Star & Garter with
            Derek, before moving up to Dunblane, where I now call home. A few
            years later, Derek retired, moved away up north, and gave up his
            season ticket. It was tough to see him go, but we still communicate
            one way or another nearly every day, so although I don't see him
            much, he is still up there as the most important person in my life
            that I haven't fathered or slept with.
          </p>

          <p>
            Although I work in Glasgow, in the shadow of the union flags of the
            bristol bar, and a stone's throw from cellic park, I am lucky enough
            to work with one of my pals, Calum. A fellow Jambo, we met at
            university, drifted apart for a few years before he joined my
            company just before Covid. He is annoyingly optimistic about almost
            everything, but he is fair and level headed when it comes to fitba.
            The eternal fence sitter when predicting scores, he keeps me
            grounded and we talk football every day. When surrounded by green
            and blue, I urge everyone to get a Calum.
          </p>

          <p>
            After many years of battling with stuttering illegal streams, or
            being in the pub when I should be spending quality time at home with
            my family, it all of a sudden became a lot easier to watch a lot of
            football at home, and at the same time screw over the TV companies
            that have helped increase the gap between the old firm and the rest
            of the league. So I was now able to see a lot more fitba, while
            partaking in my vices, and that brings us nicely to season 2024/25.
          </p>

          <p>
            The 2024/25 season was, in a word, grim. From the very start there
            was a feeling that something wasn't right — no identity, no
            consistency, no fight, and absolutely no enjoyment in watching us.
            Performances drifted between boring and embarrassing, Tynecastle
            became flat and frustrated, and every tiny bit of optimism was
            quickly beaten out of the support. Critchley somehow managed to make
            a Hearts team with decent players look utterly lifeless, which takes
            some doing considering some of the managers we've survived over the
            years - I mean, it was no Cathro, but not far off. By the end, I
            think everyone was just exhausted.
          </p>

          <p>
            But when the new season beckoned, McInnes joined, and against all
            odds retained Shankland's services, it felt different...
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section id="the-season" class="match-section">
      <article class="panel" style="line-height:1.7">
        <div class="section-heading story-section-heading">
          <span>The Season</span>
          <small>
            <a href="#top" class="back-to-top">Back to top ↑</a>
          </small>
        </div>
        <p>
          If you're just starting from here, I'd say you've missed nothing — but
          if you'd like to read a few paragraphs about a daft big lad from
          Corstorphine, click the link above for a bit of a laugh.
        </p>

        <p>
          2025/26 felt special from the word go. We had a manager I'd admired
          for years. My wife is an Aberdeen fan, so I'd watched a lot of
          Aberdeen games, and we all know what he did for them. Challenging
          (kinda) Celtic a couple of times, winning a couple of trophies — we
          all knew he was capable. He just needed a wee bit of cash and a wee
          bit of support.
        </p>

        <p>
          Persuading Shanks to stay was massive, and after the four League Cup
          games and the opening victory against Aberdeen, I felt he was the man
          for me, and after last year, finishing above the wee team, as ever,
          was the priority. And it looked very doable.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>August</strong> was crazy. Findlay's starring role and injury-time
          winner against United showed a resilience that had been missing from our
          team for a long time. While the 3–3 draw against Motherwell showed there
          was still a lot of work to do, it also showed us that McInnes was capable
          of changing things mid-game and making a difference. The away victory at
          Livingston was much the same — slow start, make changes, rescue the three
          points with seconds to spare. As we all know, this would become our MO throughout
          the season, but coming away from the plastic pitch with three points was
          always the priority. The penalties defeat against St Mirren was a disappointment,
          but let's be honest — it was the diddy cup. And as good as a wee cup run
          is, my thoughts were well and truly on the league campaign.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>September</strong> only brought two games due to pesky World Cup
          qualifiers. But two great games they were. First up: Russell Martin's Rangers.
          Currently winless, I expected the usual collapse against them. But thanks
          to one of many truly terrible refereeing/VAR decisions during this season,
          Shankland's goal stood. A rebound from a saved penalty and it's 0–2. First
          win at Ibrox since 2014, and the lead is maintained over Celtic. A statement
          victory over Falkirk followed. Three great goals and a wonderful team performance
          had the media asking the obvious question — could we sustain it? My answer
          — as it was for almost all of the rest of the season — was no. A constant
          footballing pessimist, I've seen too many football disappointments to get
          carried away in September.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>October</strong> started nervously with a difficult game at Tynecastle
          against Hibs. They were the better team and deserved at least a point. But
          Halkett stepped up and headed home the criminally underused (in my opinion)
          Kerjota cross. I don't have enough words to tell you how much I rate Halkett,
          and the fact he wasn't even considered for any of Clarke's squads is an
          embarrassment. How Hanley is anywhere near that squad while Halkett is still
          capless is something nobody will ever be able to explain to me. A walk in
          the park at Rugby Park preceded our second victory over the Old Firm so
          far that year. A commanding performance over a team bereft of confidence
          sent us eight points clear, and Brendan Rodgers walked away for a second
          time. Next came a trip to Paisley against a St Mirren team playing their
          best football of the season. A 2–2 draw sounds crap after two Old Firm wins
          and a derby victory, but they were playing well and really tough to beat
          — classic Stephen Robinson football. We came from behind twice and, honestly,
          a draw was fair.
        </p>

        <p>
          A convincing four goals without reply against Dundee at the start of <strong
            >November</strong
          > completed the first quarter with us nine points ahead of Celtic. It was
          around this time twenty years ago that it all went wrong, but without Mad
          Vlad to ruin things, I felt confident this could last. Not "win the league"
          confident — but "Europa League, beat the Hibees" confident. And that was
          enough for me.
        </p>

        <p>
          However, it started to go a wee bit awry here. Dominant against United
          at home, but only a point. Defeat to Aberdeen (always a difficult game
          in my household) despite being the better team. A nil nil draw away to
          Motherwell - although it could be said that was a good point
          considering Motherwell were the much better side. Three damaging
          scores, that had the pundits questioning whether we had it in us to go
          all the way. Fortunately the old firm were also struggling so the 9
          point lead after the Dundee game was only reduced to 5, but the
          confidence had definitely taken a bit of a battering. We knew that
          next month was gonna be tough - both the old firm and Hibs away.
          Things were getting tense.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>December</strong> looked like it was going to start OK. A more controlled
          first half against Killie, followed by a 49th minute opener. Things were
          getting back on track. Or so we thought. We just couldn't get that second
          goal and paid the price when they equalised in the last minute, doing to
          us what we had done to everyone else all season. Gutted. Celtic Park in
          4 days looked like a very tricky prospect. But this was Wilfried Nancy's
          debut - and we all remember how entertaining that time was. Shocking defending
          allowed a Braga goal to stand, and a great header from distance from McEntee
          gave us a deserved 2-1 victory and we were three points clear. Victory over
          Falkirk while Celtic were losing the diddy cup allowed us to go six points
          clear. A fourth old firm victory followed - 2-1 at home to Rangers kept
          us six ahead of Celtic while Rangers, under Danny Rohl were 12 back. What
          a position to be in - Merry Christmas everyone!
        </p>

        <p>
          Obviously, Hibs felt the need to ruin the festive cheer. Three up just
          after half time, we were a shadow of our former selves before
          something changed. Shanks pulled one back in the 75th minute. Cammy
          made it 3-2 with just a couple of minutes and injury time. But the
          Hibs goalkeeper denied us too many times for us to pull off our second
          three goal comeback of the season. Obviously gutted, but as Calum said
          "It's 2026 and we're still top of the league."
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>January</strong> is here - its a new year, and we've got six games
          this month. First up, Livi at home. A hard fought game in which we emerge
          with a 1-0 victory. Livi played well and caused us a few difficulties towards
          the end but its a solid victory. Next up is <stong>that</stong> save by
          the legend that is Craig Gordon. We go one up in controversial circumstances
          - Cammy takes a free kick from the wrong position, while its still moving
          and Braga scores. Dundee understandably upset but the goal stands. Then
          Schwolow gets a red card after a VAR intervention - no real complaints tbh
          - red card all day for me. Braga off, Craig on and after a few run of the
          mill saves, he saves the three points with a Banks-esque dive to the left.
          Classic Craig Gordon - Scotland's Number One!
        </p>

        <p>
          Next up St Mirren. And another red card. Beni this time. But no wonder
          saves by Gordon required. A defiant 2-0 victory keeps us six points
          ahead of Celtic. Then another penalty shootout defeat, this time by
          Falkirk, sends us out of the Scottish Cup at the first hurdle.
          Disappointing, but as I mentioned earlier, the league was the focus
          and I wasn't too downhearted (many Jambos won't agree with this I
          know, and I'm sorry) as a cup run might have hindered our league
          progress. Celtic then came to Tynecastle and another late goal
          salvaged a point. A great Nygren free kick gave them the lead, before
          Findlay equalised just after half time. Yang put them two up before
          Trusty was sent off for a VAR decided last man challenge. I wasn't
          convinced that it was last man, but was happy to take it. Braga
          equalised with 3 minutes to go and our 4 point lead was intact. A
          convincing 3-0 away to United meant we ended January “still top of the
          league”.
        </p>

        <p>
          Our big problem over this period, however, was the loss of both Devlin
          (St Mirren game) and Shankland (Falkirk game) to injury. We saw them
          both on the sidelines at every game, wishing for a speedy recovery -
          oh how different things might have been had they been fit for these 8
          weeks.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>February</strong> was a mixed bag of results. Another red card against
          St Mirren meant not only did we play with 10 men, it meant Halkett would
          be missing for next two games - against Hibs and Rangers. A late goal from
          the hilariously named Freckleton consigned us to our third defeat of the
          season. Very disappointing and pretty damaging. With Cammy and Shanks injured
          for the foreseeable future, and Halkett suspended, the game against Hibs
          was always gonna be tough. And it proved to be. But a Magnusson tap in sent
          us to a 1-0 victory! McInnes hugged a ball boy and we were still 6 points
          clear. In the next game, Chermiti continued his "I can only perform against
          the big teams" strategy by bagging a hat-trick in a well deserved 4-2 victory.
          We played well in the first half, going ahead twice, but they absolutely
          annihilated us in the second half. All of a sudden, Rangers are back in
          the race, 2 points behind us, with Celtic a further point behind them.
        </p>

        <p>
          Then followed four 1-0's at the end February and into <strong
            >March</strong
          >. 3 wins over Falkirk, Aberdeen and Dundee at home. And a defeat away
          to Killie. We were not playing well, but we were getting results
          (just). It wasn't pretty to watch, and we also lost Magnusson to
          injury. I know he's not a glamorous footballer, but I love him. He
          gives everything when he is on the pitch - the epitome of what I want
          from a Jambo midfielder.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>April</strong> brings the last two games before the split. Away
          to Livi and home to Motherwell. Obviously we are most focused on the tricky
          visit of Motherwell, and the Livi game should be a walk in the park. We've
          got a 100% record against them and they are the bottom of the league, all
          but relegated. But no, we start badly again, and see a 5th minute goal from
          Stevie May put us one down. We draw level before the break from a goal from
          our returning captain, and then go ahead just after the break. But Livi
          rescue a point and get the media questioning whether we have the bottle
          for the fight with an equaliser 7 minutes later. An opportunity missed.
          The Motherwell game was no less tense - 1-0 down until a 61st minute equaliser
          from Braga, we finally get the victory from a Shankland penalty and a Kabore
          strike in the dying minutes of the game. But the damage had been done 6
          days earlier at Livingston. We go into the split three ahead of Celtic and
          4 ahead of Rangers.
        </p>

        <p>
          The split favours Celtic - they have both Hearts and Rangers at home.
          The conspiracy theorists will tell you that the systemic bias in the
          SFA have done this on purpose, and while I'm generally a "swings and
          roundabouts" kinda guy, it did feel that someone up there didn't want
          us to win this league. Obviously results and subsequent enquiries in
          the coming weeks will maybe back this up, but I'm not here for that.
          If we want to win this league, we have to do it on our terms - we need
          to do everything we can and that starts with a visit to Easter Road.
          Unsurprisingly, this one was chaotic and emotionally charged. Hibs
          take the lead on 7 minutes through Martin Boyle and his atrocious
          hair. Then their keeper gets sent off for handling outside the box,
          and then they're reduced to 9 men after a second yellow for passlack.
          Then they score an OG to draw us level, and then Blair Spittal puts in
          an excellent second half performance and caps it off with the winning
          goal in the 86th minute. Jambos go mental in Easter Road - four games
          to go, three points clear.
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>May</strong> arrives and first up its Rangers. A shocker of a first
          half sees us go in behind to a Dijon Mustard goal. But a second half turnaround
          shows we are capable of winning this fight. Kyzi showed some of his early
          season form, Spittal impressed again and Kingsley was immense (as ever).
          We come away with a 2-1 victory and for the first time, I am actually believing
          this is possible. Rangers are now out of it. Its between us and Celtic.
          Both us and Celtic have to go to Motherwell before the final game of the
          season at Celtic Park. Could they do us the favor we need?
        </p>

        <p>
          The game against Motherwell was understandably tense and VAR handed us
          a lifeline while at 1-1. A trip on Kyzi in the box wasn't given by
          Steven McLean. VAR said "Are you sure? Go have another look" and even
          though he did have another look, he stuck with his original decision.
          I actually felt it was the right decision, but I am in the minority
          here and especially considering what happens 4 days later, I think we
          can feel let down by the official on this one. A draw really isnt
          enough but we're still ahead with two games to go.
        </p>

        <p>
          Falkirk have been a breath of fresh air this season. Lots of good
          Scottish players, playing well above their pay grade. A great manager
          who in any other year would be Manager of the Year (sorry, John). They
          started brightly but just didnt have enough to beat us. A 3-0 victory
          was just what was required. Now just need Motherwell to do us that
          favor and we're nearly home and dry. I had the game on split screen,
          watching both at the same time. Celtic 2-1 up with five minutes plus
          injury time to go. And then Motherwell score. If it stays like this,
          we can go to Celtic Park, get beat 2-0 (or 3-0, it was a bit hazy at
          this stage) and still win the league. Then the defining moment of the
          2026 season. 7 minutes into injury time, Sam Nicholson "handles" the
          ball in the box. Confirmed Rangers fan, John Beaton, doesnt give the
          penalty. But VAR (Andrew Dallas) says go and have another look.
          Despite not being a "clear and obvious error" Brother Beaton complies,
          and gives Celtic the spot kick. Iheanacho steps up and coolly slots
          the ball home in the 99th minute. The next few days are mental. The
          media explodes with all the usual cries of bias. I'm not getting into
          it cos its not what this page is about, and let’s face it, we’ve put
          up with the Glasgow teams getting the decisions since we started
          watching fitba. It was still in our own hands to win it, but it was
          going to be tough.
        </p>

        <p>
          This time there was no collapse. There was no Albert Kidd. There was
          no shame. Only pride. Pride for my team who gave absolutely everything
          and by the end had nothing left. Steinwender played the whole game
          with a limp. Beni pulled up with a gubbed hamstring after he could run
          no more. Schwolow couldn't get that decisive goal in the dying minutes
          that he so deserved. It was Celtic's year. It was Martin O'Neill's
          year. The man is older than my dad and still wearing his Sue Sylvester
          tracksuit like a 40 year old. Despite the VAR calls, and the cheating
          accusations, this had nothing to do with the Celtic players or
          management - they played the split perfectly and deserved to win the
          league.
        </p>

        <p>
          When we went one up, I dreamed it might happen. I had my wife and my
          17 year old daughter watching with me. Could it actaully happen? Could
          we banish the ghost of '86? They equalised and then <strong
            >battered</strong
          > us for the next 60 minutes. My football apathetic daughter was in tears
          for me. My wife was fuming at the eejits who ran on the pitch. My hun colleagues
          are screaming blue murder at the unfairness of it all. Me? I'm just proud.
          All the rest of it doesn't matter - we were a great team, who played a great
          season, but just didn't have enough to beat the Glasgow giant.
        </p>

        <p>But we will be back...</p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section id="the-future" class="match-section">
      <article class="panel" style="line-height:1.7">
        <div class="section-heading story-section-heading">
          <span>The Future</span>
          <small>
            <a href="#top" class="back-to-top">Back to top ↑</a>
          </small>
        </div>
        <p>
          What lies ahead for Heart of Midlothian Football Club in the future?
          Who knows? What happens to all successful underdogs? Generally the
          team gets carved up by the bigger teams, players are sold for a
          profit, new players come in. Manager might move on and a new manager
          might come in. But this is football - thats what happens.
        </p>

        <p>
          As I type this, its Sunday 24th June 2026 and all the media are
          talking about Shanks leaving and getting his "dream" move to Ibrox.
          Maybe he'll go, maybe he won't. What I do know is that this club is
          bigger than Lawrence Shankland, and bigger than Derek McInnes. It's
          about us - the biggest fan owned club in the UK. We have amazing
          people behind the scene, and we have every reason to be excited about
          next year. Champions League qualifiers start as soon as the World Cup
          ends (but realistically a wee run in the Europa is maybe the next
          logical step). Hopefully a wee run in the big cup, and maybe even a
          trophy?
        </p>

        <p>
          The Old Firm will spend big this summer, so a season like this last
          one is unlikely - but as long as we can bring some good player in,
          consolidate third place, and have some fun in the cups, that will do
          me. Tony Bloom said this was a 10-year plan. We have had one year.
          Look what he has done with Brighton and USG - we have to trust the
          process. It might be difficult at times but the people in charge of
          the club care - and that is what counts.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>
    <script>
      const button = document.querySelector(".story-disclaimer");
      const panel = document.querySelector(".story-panel");
      const backToTopLinks = document.querySelectorAll(
        ".story-disclaimer .back-to-top",
      );

      backToTopLinks.forEach((link) => {
        link.addEventListener("click", (event) => {
          event.stopPropagation();
        });
      });

      button?.addEventListener("click", () => {
        const isOpen = panel?.classList.toggle("is-open");
        button.setAttribute("aria-expanded", isOpen ? "true" : "false");
      });
    </script>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
